      "cost_context": "Zapier is still a sensible choice when the HubSpot process is small, low-risk, and easy to verify after each run, such as one form submission creating one internal task, sending one notification, or updating one non-critical field. It starts to become expensive when the workflow controls owner assignment, lifecycle stage movement, revenue reporting, onboarding, or shared CRM records across contacts, companies, deals, or tickets. At that point the real cost is not just subscription spend.",
      "when_zapier_is_still_right": "Zapier is still the right fit when the HubSpot workflow has a narrow trigger, a small number of writes, and consequences that are easy to inspect and correct manually. Good examples include a simple internal alert from a new form submission, a single-field update that does not affect reporting, or an early pilot with low submission volume. The threshold changes when the process spans multiple CRM objects, depends on exact associations, or needs guaranteed freshness and auditability. If someone on the team is already checking contacts, companies, deals, or tickets after runs to make sure the data landed correctly, that is usually the point where owned logic is worth considering.",
