    "bodyHtml": "<h2>Google Calendar workflows that often outgrow Zapier</h2>\n<p>Many teams begin with a small Google Calendar automation: create a task when a meeting is booked, notify a channel before a call, or copy an event into another team calendar. That is usually fine when the source is a single event: one-off meeting with specific start/end date-times and the workflow only needs one downstream action.</p>\n<p>The problems start when the same process has to support repeating schedules, edits to existing meetings, and writes across more than one calendar entity. A recurring event: weekly standup or other repeating series defined by RRULE/RDATE/EXDATE is not just a duplicate of a one-time booking. It has recurrence rules, instance behavior, and time-zone expansion that need explicit handling.</p>\n<p>Another common growth point is internal calendar sync. Once one workflow reads from one Google Calendar and writes to another, mismatches in permissions, default time zone, metadata, and all-day semantics can create drift that is hard to catch from run logs alone.</p>\n<h3>Post-meeting task creation</h3>\n<p>If a team wants tasks created after a client call finishes, the workflow should be anchored to Event Ended so the action runs after the actual meeting occurrence rather than only when the meeting was first created.</p>\n<h3>Recurring meeting operations</h3>\n<p>The practical rule is simple: do not rely on New Event for repeated schedules. For recurring work, use Event Start or another time-relative design for each occurrence so a weekly meeting is handled when it actually happens.</p>\n<h3>Calendar copy and mirror jobs</h3>\n<p>Copying events from one calendar to another requires more than field mapping. The process has to preserve event identity, respect all-day versus timed values, and account for the target calendar&#039;s default time zone.</p>\n<h2>What a direct Google Calendar replacement should control</h2>\n<p>A direct replacement should start with the workflow contract in Google Calendar terms. New Event or New or Updated Event are the most common trigger choices for automations that react to event creation and edits, but they are not the right choice for every scheduling process.</p>\n<p>For recurring schedules or actions tied to the meeting itself, Event Start and Event Ended are the safer triggers for recurring schedules or for workflows that need time-relative execution. That shift alone fixes many quiet misses where the meeting exists but no downstream action runs for the intended occurrence.</p>\n<p>Update logic also needs explicit identity handling. Zapier’s documented constraint matters here: Update Event only changes filled fields, and older events may not appear in the Event dropdown; updating older items requires Find Event to fetch the Event ID first.</p>\n<h3>Trigger selection</h3>\n<p>The scoped brief should say exactly whether the process reacts to create, update, start time, or end time, and the implementation should use the Google Calendar trigger that matches that behavior.</p>\n<h3>Time handling</h3>\n<p>Google Calendar event start.dateTime needs a time zone offset unless timeZone is explicitly specified; for recurring events, timeZone is required and defines recurrence expansion. That rule should be validated before reminders, copies, or follow-up actions are sent.</p>\n<h3>Safe writes and edits</h3>\n<p>A reliable build stores returned identifiers, avoids loose title matching, and updates the intended event on the intended calendar rather than whichever recent item happens to appear in a selector.</p>\n<h2>Risks worth scoping before rebuild work starts</h2>\n<p>A replacement project should scope more than the happy path. It needs to cover what happens when a recurring series changes, when one occurrence is edited separately from the series, when an attendee updates the time, or when a source calendar and destination calendar use different assumptions about date-only events.</p>\n<p>Time handling is often the most expensive hidden issue. Events land on the wrong date or time when Zapier, the trigger app, and Google Calendar time zones do not match, or when all-day vs timed fields are mapped incorrectly. Those cases should be tested with real examples from the business calendar, not assumed from account settings.</p>\n<p>The point is not to overbuild every schedule. It is to identify the workflow paths where a missed event, a bad copy, or a wrong update creates manual repair work for the team.</p>\n<h3>Recurring series exceptions</h3>\n<p>A recurring series can be changed at the series level or at one specific occurrence, so the implementation must know whether it is acting on the rule, the expanded instance, or an exception.</p>\n<h3>Calendar identity drift</h3>\n<p>Sync jobs become fragile when different calendars have different permissions, defaults, or ownership. The brief should identify every calendar entity involved and who controls each one.</p>\n<h3>Search versus exact lookup</h3>\n<p>Searching by title and approximate time is not enough for reliable updates. A better build records the Event ID it created or reads it back before changing anything later.</p>\n<h2>What to include in the GetForked brief</h2>\n<p>Start with the real operating workflow, not the current Zap steps. Name the source Google Calendar, any destination calendars, the downstream systems touched, and the exact outcome expected for both a one-off meeting and a recurring schedule.</p>\n<p>Include examples that cover edge cases: a single event, a recurring event, an all-day booking, an older meeting that needs an edit, and any calendar copy between teams. That gives the approved match enough context to scope trigger choice, event identity, and time handling correctly.</p>\n<p>If the current workflow already fails, describe the failure in plain operational terms. Useful examples include a weekly meeting not producing tasks, reminders arriving an hour late after a time-zone shift, or edits to older events failing because no Find Event step retrieves the current identifier.</p>\n<h3>Inputs that improve scoping</h3>\n<p>Provide sample event payloads, calendar IDs, expected run volume, downstream write targets, and whether the workflow should react instantly or relative to Event Start or Event Ended.</p>\n<h3>Rules worth documenting</h3>\n<p>Write down what counts as a valid meeting, how cancellations should be handled, whether all-day events should be ignored or transformed, and when a person should approve a change.</p>\n<h3>Handover requirements</h3>\n<p>Ask for plain-English documentation that explains trigger choice, recurrence handling, time-zone rules, stored identifiers, retry behavior, and how the team should inspect failures after launch.</p>",
