    "introSummary": "Facebook Lead Ads usually sits in the middle of a simple promise: a prospect submits an Instant Form on a Facebook Page, and that lead should appear in HubSpot, Salesforce, Keap, or Google Sheets fast enough for sales to act.\n\nWhat makes the setup unreliable is the production handoff. A test lead can look fine during setup, then live submissions fail because Meta Lead Access is not granted as CRM access to Zapier specifically, the selected lead form changed, or the page connection no longer has the right admin access.",
    "heroSummary": "Facebook Lead Ads usually sits in the middle of a simple promise: a prospect submits an Instant Form on a Facebook Page, and that lead should appear in HubSpot, Salesforce, Keap, or Google Sheets fast enough for sales to act.\n\nWhat makes the setup unreliable is the production handoff. A test lead can look fine during setup, then live submissions fail because Meta Lead Access is not granted as CRM access to Zapier specifically, the selected lead form changed, or the page connection no longer has the right admin access.",
    "problemSummary": "The risky part of a Facebook Lead Ads workflow is not the ad or the Instant Form itself. It is the assumption that a successful sample run means live routing is safe. In practice, a test lead created from Meta's lead testing tool can populate the trigger while real submissions from the selected Facebook Page and selected lead form never reach the CRM destination. That happens when the connected user loses admin access, when Meta lead permissions were never granted correctly in production, or when marketing updates or duplicates the lead form and Facebook assigns a new form ID.",
    "replacementSummary": "An owned replacement defines the event in operational terms before anything is mapped downstream: New lead created from the selected Facebook Page and selected lead form. From there, the intake service records the Facebook Page, Instant Form identifier, submission time, payload version, and delivery state for each lead. It also treats permissions as part of the workflow contract, because Facebook lead data can reach Zapier configuration/test mode but fail in production if Meta Lead Access is not granted as CRM access to Zapier specifically.",
    "uniqueContentAngle": "Replace Zapier lead routing from Facebook Ads with custom CRM ingestion pipelines",
    "bodyHtml": "<h2>What a Facebook Lead Ads replacement actually needs to cover</h2>\n<p>A real replacement starts with the campaign boundary, not with a loose idea of lead capture. Which Facebook Page is allowed to send leads, which lead form / Instant Form is active, which CRM destination should receive accepted submissions, and which secondary systems such as Google Sheets or internal alerts are required.</p>\n<p>From there, the workflow needs a durable intake record for every submission. That record should show when the lead was received, which page and form produced it, which fields were accepted, whether it matched an existing contact, which destinations were written successfully, and why any step failed or paused for review.</p>\n<h3>Typical intake scope</h3>\n<p>A common Facebook Lead Ads setup starts when a prospect submits a Facebook lead form attached to a lead-gen ad, then the system validates email, phone, campaign source, consent, and routing rules before writing the lead into HubSpot, Salesforce, Keap, or Google Sheets.</p>\n<h3>Why a single intake layer matters</h3>\n<p>If the CRM write, spreadsheet log, and sales alert are all driven separately, teams lose a single source of truth. One intake layer keeps the same facebook lead payload, validation logic, and delivery history across every destination.</p>\n<h2>Where Facebook lead routing usually breaks in production</h2>\n<p>The most common production failure is false confidence from setup testing. A test lead created from Meta&#039;s lead testing tool can confirm that mapping works in the editor, while live traffic still fails because Meta Lead Access is not granted as CRM access to Zapier specifically.</p>\n<p>Another repeat problem is form drift. Marketing edits the offer, duplicates the Instant Form, or launches a fresh lead form for a new ad set. Facebook assigns a new form ID, but the automation remains tied to the previous one, so the team sees leads inside Meta while the CRM destination stays empty.</p>\n<h3>Permission and page ownership problems</h3>\n<p>Each connection is page-specific, so the person and page behind the integration matter. If admin access changes, the Facebook Page may stop connecting properly or the trigger may stop firing without an obvious issue inside the destination system.</p>\n<h3>Field-shape and schema problems</h3>\n<p>Facebook Lead Ads can expose both raw versus regular fields, and downstream systems often expect the cleaner formatted version. If the wrong field type is mapped, the workflow may appear active while still writing bad values into HubSpot, Salesforce, or a sheet.</p>\n<h2>What owned workflow logic does that a basic handoff does not</h2>\n<p>Owned logic treats lead routing like a controlled ingestion process rather than a trigger followed by a few app actions. It validates the selected page and selected lead form, checks the current schema, applies duplicate rules, and records the outcome of every destination write.</p>\n<p>That also makes review and troubleshooting easier. Instead of asking whether Meta, Zapier, the CRM, or the spreadsheet is wrong, the team can inspect one intake record and see whether the lead was rejected, retried, delivered, or held because something about the submission or permissions was out of policy.</p>\n<h3>Validation before write</h3>\n<p>An intake service can require that the Facebook Page, Instant Form, and required fields all match approved rules before creating or updating records downstream.</p>\n<h3>Clear recovery paths</h3>\n<p>When a destination API fails or a duplicate-contact rule blocks the write, the lead can move into retry or manual review with the original payload preserved instead of producing silent loss or partial updates.</p>\n<h2>What to include in the brief before GetForked matches the work</h2>\n<p>The brief should list every active Facebook Page, each lead form / Instant Form in scope, the CRM destination such as HubSpot, Salesforce, or Google Sheets, and what should happen to duplicates, incomplete submissions, and invalid contact data.</p>\n<p>It should also identify who controls Meta permissions, who can approve campaign or form changes, what the required response-time expectations are, whether alerts are operational or informational, and what the delivered system must include for handover.</p>\n<h3>Implementation details to request</h3>\n<p>Ask for page and form ID references, field mapping documentation, duplicate logic, retry rules, review states, delivery logs, and a test procedure that uses Meta&#039;s lead testing tool before a campaign goes live.</p>\n<h3>What the deliverable should look like</h3>\n<p>The finished work should not just be a functioning integration. It should include the owned workflow, documented assumptions, access requirements, operational notes, and enough runbook detail for your team to test changes and support the system after launch.</p>",
