    "introSummary": "A common setup watches a Google Sheets row, posts a Slack channel message, and sometimes uses a Slack reaction to a message to write triage or acknowledgment back into spreadsheets.\n\nThat setup starts drifting when sheets are edited, formulas are still calculating, or Slack channel access changes. Zapier can still handle lightweight internal notices, but owned workflow logic gives you tighter control over messages, channels, rows, ranges, and cells.",
    "heroSummary": "A common setup watches a Google Sheets row, posts a Slack channel message, and sometimes uses a Slack reaction to a message to write triage or acknowledgment back into spreadsheets.\n\nThat setup starts drifting when sheets are edited, formulas are still calculating, or Slack channel access changes. Zapier can still handle lightweight internal notices, but owned workflow logic gives you tighter control over messages, channels, rows, ranges, and cells.",
    "problemSummary": "The problem is not a single failed alert. It is losing confidence that the Slack channel message reflects the right Google Sheets row, that the message reached the intended channel, or that one sheet change did not produce multiple posts. In day-to-day work, people rename tabs, insert columns, reorder rows, and adjust formulas. That is exactly where row-based automation becomes fragile. On the Slack side, delivery depends on correct channel access, and posting can fail when a destination is private, archived, renamed, or configured incorrectly. Once duplicate alerts or silent misses appear, teams end up comparing spreadsheets and Slack messages by hand to work out what actually happened.",
    "replacementSummary": "A sturdier replacement is designed around the exact trigger set in use: New Spreadsheet Row or New or Updated Spreadsheet Row in Google Sheets, Slack message posting, and any Slack reaction write-back into the sheet. Instead of relying on row position, it stores a stable key for each Google Sheets row, validates the chosen spreadsheet and worksheet, checks required headers, ranges, and cells, and waits when Sheets may still be recalculating so outbound data is not based on transient values. For Slack delivery, it uses the channel identifier required by chat.postMessage, confirms the app has the right write scope, verifies access for private channels, applies fixed message formatting, and.",
