        {
          "h2": "Where Google Sheets and Slack usually meet in real operations",
          "paragraphs": [
            "Teams often use Google Sheets as the running log and Slack as the place where people respond. A new Google Sheets row can create a Slack channel message, and a Slack reaction can mark that same row as acknowledged, assigned, or resolved.",
            "This shows up in incident handling, request queues, finance exceptions, and shared operational trackers because spreadsheets are easy to edit and Slack is where decisions happen. The trouble starts when the workflow quietly depends on a worksheet name, trigger column, or row order that people change during normal work."
          ],
          "h3_sections": [
            {
              "h3": "Incident logs",
              "paragraph": "A row added to an incident sheet can create a formatted post in a Slack incident channel with severity, owner, and links. If responders add a Slack reaction to a message, the workflow can write that acknowledgment back into the incident row."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Internal request queues",
              "paragraph": "Operations teams often collect requests in Google Sheets and notify a Slack channel when a row reaches a certain status. Controlled routing helps different rows reach different channels, threads, or escalation paths."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Exception review",
              "paragraph": "Finance or support teams may track flagged rows in sheets and use Slack for review. In those cases, a message posted event or thread reply can become part of the audit trail before any sheet update is accepted."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "h2": "What breaks first in a Zapier-based setup",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The first visible symptom is usually duplicate noise or missing alerts, but the cause is often buried in tool behavior. Rows that are inserted, reordered, or structurally modified in Sheets can break assumptions made by row-based automation.",
            "Slack has its own operational constraints. Posting requires the correct channel identifier and appropriate write scope, and private channels require membership/access. If those conditions drift from the original setup, messages stop landing where people expect."
          ],
          "h3_sections": [
            {
              "h3": "Sheet structure drift",
              "paragraph": "Google Sheets trigger configuration is sensitive to worksheet, spreadsheet, drive, and sometimes a trigger column or a don't change sheet structure expectation. Rename a tab, move headers, insert columns, or alter ranges, and the workflow can read the wrong cells or miss the row entirely."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Recalculation timing",
              "paragraph": "A row event can fire before formulas have finished updating. In formula-heavy sheets, that means a Slack channel message may be built from incomplete values even though the sheet looks correct a moment later."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Slack destination errors",
              "paragraph": "Channel routing and message formatting are common failure points. A destination can fail because the channel is private, archived, not selected correctly during setup, or no longer available to the app posting the message."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "h2": "What a stronger implementation controls differently",
          "paragraphs": [
            "A stronger implementation separates business identity from spreadsheet position. It stores a stable key for each Google Sheets row, validates the target worksheet and headers before reading or writing, and keeps a record of every outbound Slack channel message tied to that key.",
            "It also adds controls that simple automations often skip: deduplication, retry windows, access checks, and clear logging for rows, ranges, cells, channels, and messages. That makes it possible to know not only that something failed, but exactly which row, message, or reaction needs attention."
          ],
          "h3_sections": [
            {
              "h3": "Message creation with context",
              "paragraph": "Instead of sending a thin alert, the workflow can format Slack output with owner, timestamps, status, links, and thread rules tied to the real operating process. Digest workflows reduce notification fatigue when every row should not create its own message."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Safe write-backs from Slack",
              "paragraph": "When a Slack reaction or saved message should write into Google Sheets, the workflow maps the event to the original Slack message and then to the correct row. Sensitive changes can be held for approval rather than updating cells immediately."
            },
            {
              "h3": "Operational logs and replay",
              "paragraph": "Every event can be logged with source row details, destination channel, message ID, retry status, and final outcome. If a failure occurs, the team can replay a specific event instead of rerunning the entire spreadsheet workflow."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "h2": "What to put in the brief before asking for a match",
          "paragraphs": [
            "A useful brief should define the exact trigger, the source spreadsheet and sheet, the row fields that matter, the Slack destinations, and the message format required by the team. It should also state whether the workflow is one-way from Google Sheets to Slack or whether Slack messages, thread replies, or reactions also write back.",
            "The best briefs include edge cases. Note which edits should trigger a post, which should be ignored, what counts as a duplicate, who can change sheet structure, and what should happen if the workflow cannot access a channel or the sheet is still recalculating."
          ],
